status_message: When it comes to Ebola prevention, Ohio acts. Today we issued new restrictions to protect travelers.

Ohio has taken aggressive steps to prevent Ebola in the Buckeye State. We encourage other states to make the same preparations and be ready to take action above and beyond that of the federal government. Learn more here: http://fox8.com/2014/10/18/ebola-concerns-in-northeast-ohio-governor-kasich-to-meet-with-the-cdc-today/ 

If you have any questions, please call 866-800-1404.

In preparing for Ebola, we're making sure our health professionals have the equipment they need. 

Press Release: http://goo.gl/4J2EHI

OHIO ADDING TO STOCKPILE OF HEALTH CARE 
PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT
Ohio Department of Health seeks to be ready to support possible local needs across the state

COLUMBUS – The Ohio Department of Health (ODH) is adding to its stockpile of health care personal protective equipment in order to support any requests that may come from frontline health care providers treating suspected or confirmed cases of Ebola virus infection. Ohio has no cases of Ebola, but ODH will be ready to support local health care providers if a case is confirmed.

With a team of health care workers treating a single Ebola patient using as many as 240 sets of personal protective equipment per day, hospitals can quickly use up whatever stores they may have. ODH is adding to its already large stockpile in order to support whatever requests for support may come from local hospitals.

The Ohio Department of Health currently owns a stockpile of approximately 102,122 face masks, 2,592 goggles, 1,600 shoe covers, 576 coveralls, 1,350 hoods, 105,300 gloves, 29,220 respirators, and 7,026 gowns. These figures increase daily; however, as new shipments arrive. ODH is requesting approval to use $300,000 in existing funds to acquire additional personal protective equipment. The request will be considered on Monday by the Controlling Board, a body comprised of bipartisan members of the General Assembly and an official from the Ohio Office of Budget and Management that meets every two weeks to help manage and approve the use of state funds. Hospitals also have their own stores and supply contracts to constantly replenish supplies while ODH has additional stores in regional warehouses.

This afternoon I spoke with President Obama regarding Ohio's decision to implement stronger Ebola containment protocols beyond those recommended by the Federal Government. Here in Ohio, we recognize the concerns of our citizens and health care workers, and we want to make sure we use all our powers as a state to be as prepared as possible.

status_message:
STATEMENT ON EBOLA RESPONSE ACTIVITIES IN OHIO:

I have been fully briefed on the federal, state and local activities that are underway and have directed state health officials to aggressively respond to the situation and provide local health officials every resource and support they need.  Every effort must be taken to identify those at risk, monitor their health and avoid further risk. 

Ohio has a sophisticated state and local public health network that has been preparing for this possibility for several months and those plans are now being activated.  The Department of Health’s epidemiologists are on-site in Summit County to support local efforts and are in ongoing communication with the CDC to make sure we have the most up-to-date information.

The risk to people who have had no direct contact with the nurse remains very low, but everyone is seeking to apply the lessons from Dallas and we are responding aggressively to this situation, with a priority on public communication that is open, timely and accurate.  We will continue to provide as much information as soon as possible and provide local health care providers the resources they need to keep Ohioans safe.

D'Lana has the job of transferring money into our rainy-day fund, and yesterday she moved nearly $1 billion over to set an all-time high of $1.5 billion in our state savings account. While we're proud of returning $2.7 billion to taxpayers in the form of a tax cut, increasing our rainy-day fund from 89 cents to $1.5 billion sends a message to job creators nationwide - Ohio is managing its finances right and knows how to take care of taxpayer dollars. 

http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2013/07/kasich_boosts_rainy_day_fund_t.html

Over the past several years, economic hard times have forced Ohio to dip into its rainy-day fund. Today we refilled it and have a record $1.5 billion in the state's savings account. That's up from 89 cents just three short years ago. A stable and strong state budget inspires confidence from job creators and sends a message nationwide that Ohio is back in business.

status_message: Over the past two years we've worked hard to build Ohio's rainy-day fund from $0.89 to a projected $1.9 billion in July. Some tell us to spend it all. My answer? No. A good reason why can be seen in Washington right now - the sequester. Their inability to work together could mean funding for some essential services here in Ohio dries up. If that happens, Ohioans need to know those essential services will still be there. If there is truly a rainy-day in Ohio, we've got the answer. It provides us stability, security and inspires confidence in job creators looking for a state that knows how to manage taxpayer dollars properly. And we're not giving it up. Washington, fiscal responsibility works. Just look to Ohio.

status_message:
The number of Ohio kids being trafficked across the state today could fill a large high school.  These are boys and girls in our own backyards, exploited and forced into hard labor and prostitution. The bill passed tonight to fight human trafficking sends a very loud and clear message to those that go after our kids.  If you’re going to take advantage of Ohio’s boys and girls, you’re going to 
get caught and severely punished.  Ohio has set a new national standard.  States across the country should follow our lead as we work to rid ourselves of this modern-day slave trade.  I’d like to thank Rep. Teresa Fedor, Chairman Wagoner, Chairman Bubp, and the entire Ohio legislature for their overwhelming bipartisan support of this incredibly important legislation that enhances penalties for traffickers and provides the support victims need.

Congratulations to Mayor Frank Jackson and all of Cleveland on passage of the Cleveland Plan. It’s been an honor to work with Mayor Jackson to help him get the tools he needs to lift up Cleveland’s school children and give them the educational experience they deserve.  A lot of folks said this couldn’t be done, but when people of good faith recognize a problem and come together to fix it, you can’t hold them back.  Ohio’s educational, political and business leaders set aside self-interest and came together to serve some of the most vulnerable children in our state.  It’s the kind of cooperation that Ohioans expect from their leaders and I hope it’s an example we can all follow more and more.

We started the Mid-Biennium Review process several months ago in order to improve the way government operates so it can be a better steward of taxpayers’ resources. It’s been hard work and addressed a wide array of detailed and complex issues, but the end result is increased efficiency and increased commonsense. There are some changes the General Assembly has made that we’re still reviewing, but overall I’m very pleased with the result and I appreciate President Niehaus, Speaker Batchelder, and Chairmen Amstutz and Widener, for their hard work on this legislation. Together we are transforming Ohio government to more responsibly use taxpayers’ resources to serve Ohioans.

Right now it's estimated there are 1000 boys and girls being trafficked across Ohio. That's the size of a large high school, full of children forced into modern-day slavery. For too long, Ohio law hasn't done enough to both prosecute those guilty of trafficking our kids and support the child-victims who desperately need our help. That's why I'm so proud of Representative Fedor and Chairman Bubp for making this bill a priority and of the House of Representatives for coming together to swiftly pass this important legislation.  Without the support of the FBI and its Innocence Lost Task Force, the Salvation Army, and Judge Paul Herbert, this progress would not be possible. Our children need and deserve our protection. With this bill, Ohio wakes up to what’s happening and starts putting a stop to it.
